statement.p:
Let f be defined near a point
(a,b).
Suppose the mixed partial derivatives
f_{xy} \qquad\text{and}\qquad f_{yx}
exist near (a,b) and are continuous at (a,b). Then
\boxed{f_{xy}(a,b)=f_{yx}(a,b).}

Define
F(x,y)= \begin{cases} \dfrac{xy(x^2-y^2)}{x^2+y^2}, \amp (x,y)\ne(0,0),\\[3mm] 0, \amp (x,y)=(0,0). \end{cases}
We will compute the two mixed partials at the origin.

First fix y and compute F_x(0,y). For y\ne0,

  F_x(0,y) \amp= \lim_{h\to0}\frac{F(h,y)-F(0,y)}{h}
  \amp= \lim_{h\to0}\frac{hy(h^2-y^2)}{h(h^2+y^2)}
  \amp= \lim_{h\to0}\frac{y(h^2-y^2)}{h^2+y^2}
  \amp= -y.

This formula also gives F_x(0,0)=0. Therefore
F_x(0,y)=-y.
Now differentiate with respect to y at 0:
F_{xy}(0,0)=\lim_{k\to0}\frac{F_x(0,k)-F_x(0,0)}{k}=\lim_{k\to0}\frac{-k}{k}=-1.

Now reverse the order. For x\ne0,

  F_y(x,0) \amp= \lim_{k\to0}\frac{F(x,k)-F(x,0)}{k}
  \amp= \lim_{k\to0}\frac{xk(x^2-k^2)}{k(x^2+k^2)}
  \amp= \lim_{k\to0}\frac{x(x^2-k^2)}{x^2+k^2}
  \amp= x.

This formula also gives F_y(0,0)=0. Therefore
F_y(x,0)=x.
Now differentiate with respect to x at 0:
F_{yx}(0,0)=\lim_{h\to0}\frac{F_y(h,0)-F_y(0,0)}{h}=\lim_{h\to0}\frac{h}{h}=1.

For a twice differentiable function f(x,y), the Hessian matrix of f at (a,b) is
\boxed{ H_f(a,b) = \begin{pmatrix} f_{xx}(a,b) \amp f_{xy}(a,b)\\ f_{yx}(a,b) \amp f_{yy}(a,b) \end{pmatrix}. }
If the second partials are continuous near (a,b), then f_{xy}(a,b)=f_{yx}(a,b), so the Hessian is symmetric.

subsection.p:
For a function of three variables,
f(x,y,z),
the Hessian is

  \boxed{
  H_f(a,b,c)
  =
  \begin{pmatrix}
  f_{xx} \amp f_{xy} \amp f_{xz}\\
  f_{yx} \amp f_{yy} \amp f_{yz}\\
  f_{zx} \amp f_{zy} \amp f_{zz}
  \end{pmatrix}_{(a,b,c)}.
  }

When the second partials are continuous, this matrix is symmetric across its diagonal.

In matrix form,
\boxed{ f(a+u,b+v) \approx f(a,b) + df_{(a,b)}(u,v) + \frac12 \begin{pmatrix}u\amp v\end{pmatrix} H_f(a,b) \begin{pmatrix}u\\v\end{pmatrix}. }
At a critical point, df_{(a,b)}=0. So the approximation becomes
\boxed{ f(a+u,b+v) \approx f(a,b) + \frac12 \begin{pmatrix}u\amp v\end{pmatrix} H_f(a,b) \begin{pmatrix}u\\v\end{pmatrix}. }
